# MDS Badge Style in Table Rows with Buttons

## Critical Rule

**When table rows contain BOTH status badges AND action buttons, always use `badgeStyle="outlined"` for status badges.**

This prevents visual clashing between filled badges and buttons, ensuring buttons remain the primary actionable elements in the row.

## Why This Rule Matters

- **Visual Hierarchy**: Outlined badges have lighter visual weight, allowing buttons to stand out as primary interactive elements
- **Reduced Clashing**: Filled badges with solid backgrounds compete visually with buttons
- **Professional Appearance**: Outlined badges create cleaner, more refined table layouts
- **User Focus**: Action buttons are the primary interactive elements; badges should not draw equal attention

## When to Apply This Rule

Apply `badgeStyle="outlined"` to badges when ALL of the following are true:

1. Badge is in a table row (`<tr>`)
2. Same row contains action buttons (View, Edit, Delete, etc.)
3. Badge represents status or similar categorical information

## When NOT to Use Outlined Badges

Use filled badges (`badgeStyle="filled"` or default) when:

- Badges are NOT in table rows with buttons
- Badges are in standalone contexts (cards, headers, standalone indicators)
- Badges need high visual emphasis (error alerts, critical warnings outside tables)
- Table rows have NO action buttons

## Examples

### ✅ GOOD - Outlined Badges in Rows with Buttons

```tsx
{/* Table row with status badge and action buttons */}
<tr>
  <td>Project Alpha</td>
  <td>
    <Badge variant="success" badgeStyle="outlined">Active</Badge>
  </td>
  <td className="table-actions">
    <Button variant="tertiary" size="sm">View</Button>
    <Button variant="tertiary" size="sm">Edit</Button>
    <Button variant="danger" size="sm">Delete</Button>
  </td>
</tr>
```

```tsx
{/* Status badge function for tables with action columns */}
function getStatusBadge(status: ProjectStatus) {
  switch (status) {
    case 'active':
      return <Badge variant="success" badgeStyle="outlined">Active</Badge>
    case 'pending':
      return <Badge variant="warning" badgeStyle="outlined">Pending</Badge>
    case 'completed':
      return <Badge variant="info" badgeStyle="outlined">Completed</Badge>
    case 'at-risk':
      return <Badge variant="error" badgeStyle="outlined">At Risk</Badge>
  }
}
```

### ✅ GOOD - Filled Badges in Standalone Contexts

```tsx
{/* Stat card - no buttons competing for attention */}
<div className="stat-card">
  <h3>Current Status</h3>
  <Badge variant="success">Active</Badge>
</div>
```

```tsx
{/* Alert banner - needs high visibility */}
<div className="alert-banner">
  <Badge variant="error">Critical Issue</Badge>
  <p>System maintenance required</p>
</div>
```

### ❌ BAD - Filled Badges in Rows with Buttons

```tsx
{/* Visual clashing - filled badge competes with buttons */}
<tr>
  <td>Project Alpha</td>
  <td>
    <Badge variant="success">Active</Badge> {/* Missing badgeStyle="outlined" */}
  </td>
  <td className="table-actions">
    <Button variant="tertiary" size="sm">View</Button>
    <Button variant="tertiary" size="sm">Edit</Button>
  </td>
</tr>
```

### ❌ BAD - Outlined Badges in Standalone High-Emphasis Contexts

```tsx
{/* Error notification needs strong visual weight */}
<div className="error-notification">
  <Badge variant="error" badgeStyle="outlined">Failed</Badge> {/* Too subtle */}
  <p>Transaction could not be processed</p>
</div>
```

